Fun fact: The "pupil" on a mantis's eye is actually a spot absorbing light rather than reflecting it, and moves depending on the viewer. It's an optical illusion.

>>28191151
Actually no, because each section just detects the strongest color and becomes a dot of that one color. In other words, it has a very low resolution, pixelated view of the world. An insect waifu would most likely have difficulty taking in the finer features of your face. Color vision is also a crapshoot that varies from insect to insect, though some can detect ultraviolet light. For example, bees cannot see most oranges, reds, and infrared, but can detect yellows, greens, blues, violets and ultraviolets.

From what I can see, it's sophisticated in how it receives different images through the other two eyes which it can use to detect motion, then using the other to gauge distance, with one set that's movable. It's found to be the best among other spiders, but I can't find much articles describing how detailed their vision is. One said it's on the level of a cat's vision, but that was about it. They apparently also have some issue with colors, as they can detect green light A-OK, while reds makes distance harder to judge when they leap to their target as done in an experiment when they bathe flies in a certain colored light.

Also, apparently if the motion-detecting eyes were covered, the main eyes will have no idea where to look. The sophistication seems to be how it uses it's two different sets of eyes to get its vision. Also also, a baby's eyesight is apparently almost as good as the adults, albeit with some difficulty in low light vision.
